{"text": "Find the best broker for your trading or investing needs NVIDIA\u00a0Corporation ( ) reported a blowout fourth quarter on Thursday, beating and estimates by a wide margin while sharply raising first quarter . The report\u00a0triggered a strong buy-the-news reaction, lifting the stock more than 30 points before profit taking set in, taking back about 10 points. Price action looks less impressive after noting that the stock fell more than 11 points during the regular session, in sympathy with the thousand-point decline. New highs are drying up in the developing , making it harder for leadership stocks including NVIDIA\u00a0to enter rally mode. Investors and traders are often forced to sell their strongest holdings in falling markets to compensate for losses taken in their weakest plays. This long-observed feedback loop can drop the strongest issues to multi-month lows before interested buyers gather the funds needed to start fresh uptrends. (See also: .) The company came public at a $1.83 in January 1999 and eased into a trading range between $1.33 and $2.37. It broke out in the fourth quarter, entering a trend advance at the same time the neared its historic climax. NVIDIA shares topped out at $14.67 in June 2000 and outperformed the broad market for the next 18 months, hitting a new high at $24.22 in January 2002. Sellers then took control, dropping the stock to a three-year low in the deep single digits. A strong uptrend through mid-decade ended 15 points above the 2002 high in 2007, giving way to a decline that held up relatively well during the 2008 . The stock posted a four-year low at $5.75 and bounced into the new decade, stalling at the .618 in 2011. It finally completed the round trip five years later, right after the stock took off in a\u00a0historic uptrend, driven by virtual reality and the company's connection. The monthly ended an incomplete sell cycle in April 2017, while the subsequent buy cycle reached the level in August. The indicator crossed to the bear side at the start of 2018, normally predicting six to nine months of relative weakness, but the stock has not\u00a0dropped to the level since 2011. While this highlights unusual strength in recent years, it also predicts that will eventually take control, generating a steep decline. (For more, see: .) The stock entered a powerful in August 2015, lifting above the 2011 peak (red line) at the end of 2016. It has continued to post new highs into 2018, indicating strong institutional sponsorship that should limit selling pressure during a correction. The indicator breakout line could be useful if the stock heads for lower ground, with hidden at that level likely to attract strong buying interest. Price action eased into a rising channel in June 2017, tracking logarithmic price scale more reliably than arithmetic price scale. It rallied into channel for the third time in January 2018, posting an all-time high at $249.27 and selling off with the broad market, dropping 45 points into this week's low at $204. A bounce through mid-week stalled at the .618 sell-off retracement, while Thursday's post-market advance ended near that level. This price action tells informed market players to watch the tape between $233 and $240, looking for sellers to reload positions. A rally above $240 will indicate bullish strength that may support a at the late January high. Broad market action is likely to tell the longer-term tale because corrections generate high levels, with equities moving in lockstep with sector and index . (See also: .) NVIDIA\u00a0reported a strong quarter, lifting about 25 points into the open of Friday's session. However, it will be hard for the stock to post new highs until the broad-based decline finally comes to an end. (For additional reading, check out: .) Want to learn how to invest? Delivered twice a week, straight to your inbox.", "link": "https://www.investopedia.com/news/nvidia-could-head-lower-despite-strong-quarter/?utm_campaign=rss-marketwatch&utm_source=marketwatch&utm_medium=referral", "source": "MarketWatch", "author": "Alan Farley", "tick": "NVDA", "headline": "NVIDIA Stock Could Head Lower Despite Strong Quarter | Investopedia"}
{"text": "Published: LONDON, Jan. 30, 2018 /PRNewswire/ -- Download the full report:        Growing applications of animation in the media & entertainment, healthcare & life sciences, manufacturing, and education & academics industries is expected to drive the market significantly.  The creation of dynamic content and high-end visuals has enabled the biotech, medical devices, and pharmaceutical industries to exploit the benefits of 3D animation. Animation is being used for maximizing sales, as it enables providers to emphasize and focus on the benefits of products and services by delivering an engaging, educational, and entertaining experience to the viewers.  The increasing use of 3D animation technologies is expected to influence the end-use industries positively. In case of medical science, 3D animation techniques are one of the most effective ways for communication as they display the human body in a polygonal form, which cannot be replicated using photography, sketch, and two-dimensional illustrations.  Traditionally concentrated in the developed countries, the 3D animation market has paved its way into the emerging countries such as India, China, and the Philippines owing to the increasing trend of outsourcing animation activities to these countries. In 2016, the North American region accounted for the largest revenue share of the 3D animation market. However, the Asia Pacific region is expected to witness robust growth throughout the forecast period.    \u2022 The 3D modeling segment is expected to account for the largest revenue share by 2025 and register an estimated CAGR of around 10% over the forecast period \u2022 The visual effects segment was valued at around USD 2.1 billion in 2016, primarily attributed to the increased demand from the media & entertainment industry \u2022 By 2025, the media & entertainment end-use segment is projected to account for around 35% of the total revenue share \u2022 In 2016, the North American region accounted for the largest revenue share and is anticipated to retain its dominance throughout the forecast period \u2022 Asia Pacific is projected to emerge as the fastest growing market since there is a growing emphasis on producing local animated content apart from the outsourced assignments performed by regional firms \u2022 The key players in the industry include Autodesk, Inc., Corel Corporation, Zco Corporation, Adobe Systems Incorporated, NVIDIA Corporation, and NewTek, Inc.  Download the full report:   About  Reportbuyer is a leading industry intelligence solution that provides all market research reports from top publishers  For more information: Sarah Smith Research Advisor at Reportbuyer.com Email:  Tel: +1 (718) 213 4904 Website:  View original content: SOURCE  ReportBuyer Copyright (C) 2018 PR Newswire. All rights reserved Copyright \u00a9 2018 MarketWatch, Inc.  All rights reserved. By using this site you agree to the , , and .", "link": "https://www.marketwatch.com/story/the-global-3d-animation-market-is-expected-to-reach-usd-2831-billion-by-2025-2018-01-30", "source": "MarketWatch", "author": null, "tick": "NVDA", "headline": "The global 3D animation market is expected to reach USD 28.31 billion by 2025 - MarketWatch"}
{"text": "Published: Jan 31, 2018 (ACCESSWIRE via COMTEX) -- NEW YORK, NY / ACCESSWIRE / January 31, 2018 / U.S. markets fell sharply Tuesday for the second consecutive day. Both the Dow Jones and S&P 500 experienced their largest one day drop of 2018. The Dow Jones Industrial Average dropped 1.37 percent to close at 26,076.89, while the S&P 500 Index fell 1.09 percent to close at 2,822.43. The Nasdaq Composite Index declined 0.86 percent to close at 7,402.48. Investors appear to be awaiting details from the State of the Union address by President Donald Trump on Tuesday night. \"We've had a unilateral move higher [in stocks] to start things off and people are realizing this is not sustainable,\" said Art Hogan, chief market strategist at B. Riley FBR. \"You're also seeing some cracks in the global story with interest rates rising.\" RDI Initiates Coverage on: Advanced Micro Devices, Inc.   NVIDIA Corporation   Advanced Micro Devices stock moved 3.38% lower Tuesday, to close the day at $12.87. The stock was down 7% in early trading, but saw a bounce back after reporting 4th quarter earnings that beat estimates. Adj. EPS of $0.08 was higher than the $0.05 expected by the street. Revenue was also higher at $1.48 billion compared to the expected $1.41 billion. The stock recorded a trading volume of 91,236,383 shares, which was above its three months average volume of 50,877,648 shares. In the last year, Advanced Micro Devices shares have traded in a range of 9.70 - 15.65. The share price has gained 32.68% from its 52 week low. The company's shares are currently trading above their 200-day moving average. The stock's 50-day moving average of $11.50 is below its 200-day moving average of $12.29. Shares of Advanced Micro Devices have gained roughly 25.19 percent in the past month. Access RDI's Advanced Micro Devices, Inc. Research Report at:   On Tuesday, shares of NVIDIA recorded a trading volume of 14,262,028 shares, which was above the three months average volume of 13